exists an formula_115, such that for every \"x\" in \"E\" and every formula_116, formula_117 is in \"V\". In this situation, uniform limit of continuous functions remains continuous.\nDefinition in a hyperreal setting.\nUniform convergence admits a simplified definition in a hyperreal setting. Thus, a sequence formula_40 converges to \"f\" uniformly if for all hyperreal \"x\" in the domain of formula_119 and all infinite \"n\", formula_120 is infinitely close to formula_121 (see microcontinuity for a similar definition of uniform continuity). In contrast, pointwise continuity requires this only for real \"x\".\nExamples.\nFor formula_122, a basic example of uniform convergence can be illustrated as follows: the sequence formula_123 converges uniformly, while formula_124 does not. Specifically, assume formula_125. Each function formula_123 is less than or equal to formula_127 when formula_128, regardless of the value of formula_9. On the other hand, formula_124 is only less than or equal to formula_127 at ever increasing values of formula_16 when values of formula_9 are selected closer and closer to 1 (explained more in depth further below).\nGiven a topological space \"X\", we can equip the space of bounded real or complex-valued functions over \"X\" with the uniform norm topology, with the uniform metric defined by \nformula_134\nThen uniform convergence simply means convergence in the uniform norm topology: \nformula_135.\nThe sequence of functions formula_1 \nformula_137 \nis a classic example of a sequence of functions that converges to a function formula_2 pointwise but not uniformly. To show this, we first observe that the pointwise limit of formula_1 as formula_64 is the function formula_2, given by\n formula_142\n\"Pointwise convergence:\" Convergence is trivial for formula_143 and formula_144, since formula_145 and formula_146, for all formula_16. For formula_148 and given formula_91, we can ensure that formula_25 whenever formula_24 by choosing formula_152