 via the triangle inequality to produce the desired inequality.\n&lt;templatestyles src=\"Math_proof/styles.css\" /&gt;Proof\nLet formula_233 be an arbitrary point. We will prove that formula_217 is continuous at formula_235. Let formula_236. By uniform convergence, there exists a natural number formula_5 such that\nformula_238\n(uniform convergence shows that the above statement is true for all formula_24, but we will only use it for one function of the sequence, namely formula_177).\nIt follows from the continuity of formula_241 at formula_242 that there exists an open set formula_243 containing formula_244 such that\nformula_245.\nHence, using the triangle inequality,\nformula_246,\nwhich gives us the continuity of formula_217 at formula_244.formula_249\nThis theorem is an important one in the history of real and Fourier analysis, since many 18th century mathematicians had the intuitive understanding that a sequence of continuous functions always converges to a continuous function. The image above shows a counterexample, and many discontinuous functions could, in fact, be written as a Fourier series of continuous functions. The erroneous claim that the pointwise limit of a sequence of continuous functions is continuous (originally stated in terms of convergent series of continuous functions) is infamously known as \"Cauchy's wrong theorem\". The uniform limit theorem shows that a stronger form of convergence, uniform convergence, is needed to ensure the preservation of continuity in the limit function.\nMore precisely, this theorem states that the uniform limit of \"uniformly continuous\" functions is uniformly continuous; for a locally compact space, continuity is equivalent to local uniform continuity, and thus the uniform limit of continuous functions is continuous.\nTo differentiability.\nIf formula_214 is an interval and all the functions formula_40 are differentiable and converge to a limit formula_2, it is often desirable to determine the derivative function formula_253 by taking the limit of the sequence formula_254. This is however in general not possible: even if the convergence is uniform, the limit function need not be differentiable (not even if the sequence consists of everywhere-analytic functions, see Weierstrass function), and even if it is differentiable, the derivative of the limit function need not be equal to the limit of the derivatives. Consider for instance formula_255 with uniform limit formula_256. Clearly, formula_253 is also identically zero. However, the derivatives of the sequence of functions are given by formula_258 and the sequence formula_254 does not converge to formula_260 or even to any function at all. In order to ensure a connection between the limit of a sequence of differentiable functions and the limit of the sequence of derivatives, the uniform convergence of the sequence of derivatives plus the convergence of the sequence of functions at at least one point is required:\n \"If formula_1 is a sequence of differentiable functions on formula_262 such that formula_263 exists (and is finite) for some formula_264 and the sequence formula_265 converges uniformly on formula_262, then formula_40 converges uniformly to a function formula_2 on formula_262, and formula_270 for formula_271.\"\nTo integrability.\nSimilarly, one often wants to exchange integrals and limit processes. For the Riemann integral, this can be done if uniform convergence is assumed:\n \"If formula_272 is a sequence of Riemann integrable functions defined on a compact interval formula_273 which uniformly converge with limit formula_217, then formula_217 is Riemann integrable and its integral can be computed as the limit of the integrals of the formula_276:\" formula_277\nIn fact, for a uniformly convergent family of bounded functions on an interval, the upper and lower Riemann integrals converge to the upper and lower Riemann integrals of the limit function. This follows because, for \"n\" sufficiently large, the graph of formula_40 is within \u03b5 of the graph of \"f\", and so the upper sum and lower sum of formula_40 are each within formula_280 of the value of the upper and lower sums of formula_2, respectively.\nMuch stronger theorems in this respect, which require not much more than pointwise convergence, can be obtained if one abandons the Riemann integral and uses the Lebesgue integral instead.\nTo analyticity.\nUsing Morera's Theorem, one can show that if a sequence of analytic functions converges uniformly in a region S of the complex plane, then the limit is analytic in S. This example demonstrates that complex functions are more well-behaved than real functions, since the uniform limit of analytic functions on a real interval need not even be differentiable (see Weierstrass function).\nTo series.\nWe say that formula_282 converges:\nWith this definition comes the following result:\nLet \"x\"0 be contained in the set \"E\" and each \"f\"\"n\" be continuous at \"x\"0. If formula_283 converges uniformly on \"E\" then \"f\" is continuous at \"x\"0 in \"E\". Suppose that formula_284 and each \"f\"\"n\" is integrable on \"E\". If formula_282 converges uniformly on \"E\" then \"f\" is integrable on \"E\" and the series of integrals of \"f\"\"n\" is equal to integral of the series of fn.\nAlmost uniform convergence.\nIf the domain of the functions is a measure space \"E\" then the related notion of almost uniform convergence can be defined. We say a sequence of functions formula_1 converges almost uniformly on \"E\" if for every formula_287 there exists a measurable set formula_288 with measure less than formula_289 such that the sequence of functions formula_1 converges uniformly on formula_291. In other words, almost uniform convergence means there are sets of arbitrarily small measure for which the sequence of functions converges uniformly on their complement.\nNote that almost uniform convergence of a sequence does not mean that the sequence converges uniformly almost everywhere as might be inferred from the name. However, Egorov's theorem does guarantee that on a finite measure space, a sequence of functions that converges almost everywhere also converges almost uniformly on the same set.\nAlmost uniform convergence implies almost everywhere convergence and convergence in measure.\nNotes.\n&lt;templatestyles src=\"Reflist/styles.css\" /&gt;"}
