f \"energy\" is measured in units of \"\u0127\u03c9\" and \"distance\" in units of , then the Hamiltonian simplifies to\nformula_56\nwhile the energy eigenfunctions and eigenvalues simplify to Hermite functions and integers offset by a half,\nformula_57\nformula_58\nwhere \"H\"\"n\"(\"x\") are the Hermite polynomials.\nTo avoid confusion, these \"natural units\" will mostly not be adopted in this article. However, they frequently come in handy when performing calculations, by bypassing clutter.\nFor example, the fundamental solution () of \"H\" \u2212 \"i\u2202t\", the time-dependent Schr\u00f6dinger operator for this oscillator, simply boils down to the Mehler kernel,\nformula_59\nwhere \"K\"(\"x\",\"y\";0) = \"\u03b4\"(\"x\" \u2212 \"y\"). The most general solution for a given initial configuration \"\u03c8\"(\"x\",0) then is simply\nformula_60\nCoherent states.\nThe coherent states (also known as Glauber states) of the harmonic oscillator are special nondispersive wave packets, with minimum uncertainty \"\u03c3x\" \"\u03c3p\" = &lt;templatestyles src=\"Fraction/styles.css\" /&gt;\"\u210f\"\u20442, whose observables' expectation values evolve like a classical system. They are eigenvectors of the annihilation operator, \"not\" the Hamiltonian, and form an overcomplete basis which consequentially lacks orthogonality.\nThe coherent states are indexed by formula_61 and expressed in the basis as\nformula_62\nSince coherent states are not energy eigenstates, their time evolution is not a simple shift in wavefunction phase. The time-evolved states are, however, also coherent states but with phase-shifting parameter \u03b1 instead: formula_63.formula_64\nBecause formula_65 and via the Kermack-McCrae identity, the last form is equivalent to a unitary displacement operator acting on the ground state: formula_66. Calculating the expectation values:\nformula_67\nformula_68\nwhere formula_69 is the phase contributed by complex \u03b1. These equations confirm the oscillating be